qdrant/qdrant#7250.body:
When a collection has a payload schema with an array field that is queried with nested properties, strict mode checks the wrong index keys and raises false alarms.

## Current Behavior
Let's say we have a collection with points that have the schema demonstrated with the following example:
```json 
{
  "aspects": [
    {
      "source": "some source",
      "name": "some aspect name"
    },
    {
      "source": "another source",
      "name": "another aspect name"
    }
  ]
}
```

We can index this payload with `aspects[].source` and `aspects[].name` keyword indexes for efficient queries.

If we try to use the `unindexed_filtering_retrieve` option in the strict mode config, the queries get rejected with the following error message:

```
"Bad request: Index required but not found for \"aspects.source\" of one of the following types: [keyword]. Help: Create an index for this key or use a different filter."
```

If you add the `aspects.source` index **(even though it's the wrong kind of index and hits 0 points)**, it then asks for an `aspects.name` index. If you provide both these unnecessary and unused indexes, the query runs and properly uses the `aspects[].source` and `aspects[].name` indexes.

## Steps to Reproduce
1. Open the console in Qdrant UI
2. Create a test collection with:
```
PUT /collections/test_collection
{
  "strict_mode_config": {
    "enabled": true,
    "unindexed_filtering_retrieve": false
  }
}
```
3. Create the necessary payload indexes
```
PUT /collections/test_collection/index
{
  "field_name": "aspects[].source",
  "field_schema": "keyword"
}

PUT /collections/test_collection/index
{
  "field_name": "aspects[].name",
  "field_schema": "keyword"
}
``` 

4. Perform a nested query
```
POST /collections/test_collection/points/scroll
{
  "filter": {
    "should": {
      "nested": {
        "key": "aspects",
        "filter": {
          "must": [
            {
              "key": "source",
              "match": {
                "value": "some source" 
              }
            },
            {
              "key": "name",
              "match": {
                "value": "some aspect name" 
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```
6. Observe one of the two possible errors
```
{
  "error": "Bad request: Index required but not found for \"aspects.source\" of one of the following types: [keyword]. Help: Create an index for this key or use a different filter."
}

{
  "error": "Bad request: Index required but not found for \"aspects.name\" of one of the following types: [keyword]. Help: Create an index for this key or use a different filter."
}
```

7. Either disable the strict mode, or create the unnecessary and unused indexes as a workaround

## Expected Behavior
Query should run without any errors.

## Possible Solution
Nested queries should check if array indexes exist.

## Context (Environment)
We had to disable the strict mode in our production cluster (v1.15.4 running on Qdrant Cloud) as a workaround.

## Detailed Description
[This](https://github.com/qdrant/qdrant/blob/v1.15.4/lib/collection/src/operations/verification/mod.rs#L116) check seems to be failing and the [one_unindexed_key](https://github.com/qdrant/qdrant/blob/master/lib/collection/src/collection/payload_index_schema.rs#L124) method implementation seems to be the culprit.

